locally finite measure `μ` on `α`, any finite measure `ν` on `α'`, and any
`f` such that `f` is `p`-locally integrable with respect to `μ`, we have
`‖T f‖_{L^p(ν)} ≤ c * ‖f‖_{L^p(μ)} * ν(α')^{1/p'}`.
Here `p'` is the conjugate exponent to `p`, and `‖f‖_{L^p(μ)}` is the
Lorentz norm of `f` with respect to `μ`.

The theorem states that if `T` satisfies certain conditions related to linearity,
continuity, and boundedness, then `T` is of Lorentz type. These conditions are
phrased in terms of the behavior of `T` on indicator functions and its continuity
properties.
